TY  - JOUR
AU  - Bailey, Martha J.
T1  - More Power to the Pill: The Impact of Contraceptive Freedom on Women's Life Cycle Labor Supply*
PY  - 2006
Y1  - 2006/02/01
DO  - 10.1093/qje/121.1.289
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 121
IS  - 1
SP  - 289
EP  - 320
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - The release of Enovid in 1960, the first birth control pill, afforded U. S. women unprecedented freedom to plan childbearing and their careers. This paper uses plausibly exogenous variation in state consent laws to evaluate the causal impact of the pill on the timing of first births and extent and intensity of women's labor-force participation. The results suggest that legal access to the pill before age 21 significantly reduced the likelihood of a first birth before age 22, increased the number of women in the paid labor force, and raised the number of annual hours worked.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/qje/121.1.289
ER  - 



